 The diagonal of a square divides it into two 45-45-90 triangles. In a 45-45-90 triangle, the hypotenuse is $ \sqrt{2} $ times the length of each leg. Let the side length of the square be $ s $. Then the diagonal is $ s\sqrt{2} $. Given that the diagonal is $ 10\sqrt{2} $ cm, we have:

\begin{align*}
s\sqrt{2} &= 10\sqrt{2} \\
s &= 10
\end{align*}

The area of the square is $ s^2 = 10^2 = 100 $ square centimeters. </think> <answer> 100 </answer>

